article.description:
Katie Smith scored 25 points as the Minnesota Lynx ended a five-game losing streak by beating the Orlando Miracle
67-59 Saturday night.
article.headline: Smith's 25 helps Lynx end losing streak
article.linkText: Lynx end five-game slide at Miracle's expense
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The result was the only thing that mattered
to the Minnesota Lynx on Saturday night.

	   Katie Smith scored 25 points as the Lynx ended a five-game
losing streak by beating the Orlando Miracle 67-59 Saturday night.

	   Minnesota (5-8) overcame a seven-minute scoreless stretch late in
the game to win for the first time since beating Portland on June
13.

	   "A lot of people are counting us out already,'' said
Minnesota's Svetlana Abrosimova. "But this season is only
beginning. Nobody is giving up.''

	   The Lynx made their first four 3-pointers of the second half,
and took their biggest lead of the game at 65-48 when Kristi
Harrower hit a three with 7:53 to play.

	   Minnesota didn't score again until Smith hit two free throws
with 47.1 seconds to play. But Orlando could only whittle the
deficit to six points while the Lynx went cold.

	   "I wasn't able to breathe a sigh of relief until Katie went to
the line,'' said Lynx coach Brian Agler. "I knew she would knock
those down.''

	   Smith scored 15 points in the first half as the Lynx capitalized
on 14 Orlando turnovers for 17 points.

	   The Miracle (7-6) committed 18 turnovers for the game and shot
just 38 percent.

	   "We knew what they liked to do offensively,'' Smith said. "And
we came out and made a concerted effort to take those things
away.''

	   The Lynx closed the first half with a 22-9 run to take a 40-30
lead at intermission, then built a big lead in the second half with
some hot 3-point shooting.

	   The Lynx hit the first four 3-pointers they took in the second
half. Smith, who made four in the game, put Minnesota up 56-39 on a
3-pointer with 12:34 remaining.

	   Orlando scored the next five points but Smith answered with
another three. The Lynx made eight of 15 3-pointers in the game.

	   The Lynx also got a lift with Abrosimova's return to the lineup.
She scored 14 points and added 10 rebounds, registering her second
double-double of the year. She had sat out the team's previous game
against Houston with a sore back.

	   "I wouldn't have been able to play tonight if I'd played
against Houston,'' Abrosimova said. "I'm still not 100 percent,
but it's like night and day.''

	   Katie Douglas scored 16 points to lead Orlando. The Miracle have
lost three in a row, all on the road.
